{{Infobox Aviation
|name=General aviation in the United Kingdom
|image=Image:Cessna.f172g.g-bgmp.arp.jpg
|caption=Traditional general aviation [[Fixed-wing aircraft|fixed-wing]] [[light aircraft]], the most numerous class of aircraft in the sector
}}
'''General aviation in the United Kingdom''' has been defined as a civil [[aircraft]] operation other than a [[Airline|commercial air transport]] flight operating to a schedule. Although the [[International Civil Aviation Organization]] (ICAO) excludes any form of remunerated aviation from its definition, some commercial operations are often included within the scope of general aviation (GA) in the [[United Kingdom|UK]]. The sector operates [[business jet]]s, [[rotorcraft]], [[Reciprocating engine|piston]] and [[jet-engine]]d [[fixed-wing aircraft]], [[glider]]s of all descriptions, and [[Aerostat|lighter than air]] craft. Public transport operations include business (or corporate) aviation and [[air taxi]] services, and account for nearly half of the economic contribution made by the sector. Other commercial GA activities are aerial work, such as [[Aerial survey|surveying]] and [[Air Ambulances in the United Kingdom|air ambulances]], and [[flight training]], which plays an important role in the supply of pilots to the commercial air transport (CAT) industry. [[Private aviation|Private flying]] is conducted for personal transport and recreation. It includes a strong vintage aircraft movement, and encompasses a range of [[air sports]], such as racing, [[aerobatics]], and [[parachuting]], at which British teams and individuals have succeeded in international competition.

Of the 27,000 civil aircraft registered in the UK, 96 per cent are engaged in GA operations, and annually the GA fleet accounts for between 1.25 and 1.35 million hours flown. The single most common class of aircraft is the fixed-wing [[light aircraft]] associated with traditional GA, but the main area of growth over the last 20 years has been in the use of more affordable aircraft, such as [[Ultralight aviation|microlights]], [[Homebuilt aircraft|amateur built]] aeroplanes, and smaller [[helicopters]]. There are 28,000 [[Private Pilot Licence]] holders, and 10,000 [[Gliding#Badges|certified glider pilots]]. Some of the 19,000 pilots who hold professional licences are also engaged in GA activities. Although GA operates from more than 1,800 [[aerodrome]]s and landing sites, ranging in size from large [[regional airport]]s to farm strips, over 80 per cent of GA activity is conducted at 134 of the larger aerodromes. The GA industry, which is around 7 per cent the size of its CAT cousin, employs 12,000 people, and contributes <U+00A3>1.4 billion to the UK economy.

GA is regulated by the [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|Civil Aviation Authority]] (CAA), although regulatory powers are being increasingly transferred to the [[European Aviation Safety Agency]] (EASA). The main focus is on standards of [[airworthiness]] and [[Pilot licensing in the United Kingdom|pilot licensing]], and the objective is to promote high standards of safety. At the lighter end of the GA spectrum some regulatory authority is devolved to representative bodies, and [[gliding]] is in transition from a self-regulatory model to more formal governance by EASA. [[Airspace]] regulation necessary to protect an increasing number of CAT operations has reduced the area in which GA flights can be freely conducted. The growth in CAT is also making access to larger airports more difficult for the GA sector, and smaller aerodromes are vulnerable to closure and re-development for more profitable uses. The UK [[Town and country planning in the United Kingdom|planning system]] has no remit to consider the national significance of GA public transport operations, and generally does not favour the development of smaller aerodromes catering to the GA market. The planning process has become a mechanism for addressing local aerodrome-related environmental issues which, particularly regarding noise, are the main subjects of public criticism levelled at GA.

==Definitions==

[[Image:G-oldw (2099547348).jpg|thumb|left|Business aviation is a commercial activity that is considered part of the GA sector.]]
The [[International Civil Aviation Organization]] (ICAO) defines general aviation (GA) as "an aircraft operation other than a commercial air transport operation or an aerial work operation." It defines [[Airline|commercial air transport]] (CAT) as "an aircraft operation involving the transport of passengers, cargo or mail for remuneration or hire", and aerial work as "an aircraft operation in which an aircraft is used for specialized services such as agriculture, construction, photography, surveying, observation and patrol, search and rescue, aerial advertisement, etc."<ref name="CAA_Definition">{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/33/RegReview.pdf|title= Regulatory Review of General Aviation in the United Kingdom|accessdate=2008-06-03 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07-06|pages= p. 3<U+2013>1 (section 3.1) and p. D-1 (Annex D)}}</ref>

Organisations in the [[United Kingdom]] (UK) describe GA in less restrictive terms that include elements of [[commercial aviation]]. The British Business and General Aviation Association interprets it to be "all aeroplane and helicopter flying except that performed by the major airlines and the Armed Services".<ref name="BBGA_Industry">{{cite web |url= http://www.bbga.aero/aviation-industry.php|title= What is General Aviation?|accessdate=2008-06-03 |publisher= British Business and General Aviation Association}}</ref> The General Aviation Awareness Council applies the description "all Civil Aviation operations other than scheduled air services and non-scheduled air transport operations for remuneration or hire".<ref name="GAAC_Definition">{{cite web |url= http://www.gaac.co.uk/ga/what_is_ga.htm|title= What is General Aviation?|accessdate=2008-06-03 |publisher= General Aviation Awareness Council|date= 2006-07-06}}</ref> For the purposes of a strategic review of GA in the UK, the [[Civil Aviation Authority (United Kingdom)|Civil Aviation Authority]] (CAA) defined the scope of GA as "a civil aircraft operation other than a commercial air transport flight operating to a schedule", and considered it necessary to depart from the ICAO definition and include aerial work and minor CAT operations.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= Overview of the Strategic Review, p. i, paras. 9<U+2013>10}} This article uses the CAA description to define the scope of general aviation in the UK, on the basis that this organisation is the regulatory body for aviation in the UK and the publisher of a key source.</ref>

==History==

[[Image:Amy Johnson jason india.jpg|thumb|[[Amy Johnson]] and her [[de Havilland DH.60 Moth]] 'Jason']]
The first [[aerodrome]] in the UK was established by the [[Royal Aero Club|Aero Club]] at Muswell Manor on the [[Isle of Sheppey]], and in May 1909 it was the venue of the first flight conducted in the country by a British [[Aviator|pilot]], [[John Moore-Brabazon, 1st Baron Brabazon of Tara|John Moore-Brabazon]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.muswellmanorholidaypark.com/aviation_history.htm|title= Aviation History at Muswell Manor in Leysdown|accessdate=2008-07-04 |publisher= Muswell Manor Holiday Park}} The 16 October 1908 flight at [[Farnborough Airfield|Farnborough]] by American [[Samuel Franklin Cody|Samuel F. Cody]] is [http://www.raes.org.uk/2008/watershed.htm officially recognised] as the first powered aeroplane flight in Britain.</ref> In 1910 the Aero Club was granted the Royal prefix, took responsibility for controlling all [[Private aviation|private flying]] in the UK, and started issuing the first British pilot licences. The introduction of the [[de Havilland DH.60 Moth]] in 1925 revolutionised light aviation, and the Royal Aero Club, recognising the "vital necessity of promoting civil flying", formed the Light Aeroplane Club scheme. Between 1925 and 1939 around 60 [[flying club]]s were started, and more than 5,000 pilots were trained.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.royalaeroclub.org/history.htm|title= A Brief History of the Royal Aero Club|accessdate=2008-07-04 |publisher= [[Royal Aero Club]]}}</ref>

During [[World War II]] civil aerodromes were taken over for military use, existing military airfields were expanded, and new ones were built.<ref>{{cite book | last = Rowley | first = Trevor | title = The English Landscape in the Twentieth Century | publisher = [[Continuum International Publishing Group]] | date = 2006 | pages = p. 318 | url = http://books.google.com/books?id=SZWI2kYEhTcC&pg=RA1-PA318&lpg=RA1-PA318&dq=%22Emergency+Powers+(Defence)+Act%22+airfields&source=web&ots=EqV75CxIdn&sig=up-tUV1gXi2nuzeWbRQ6mvQAbEY&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=3&ct=result#PRA1-PA310,M1 | isbn = 1852853883}}</ref> This resulted in a significant inventory of facilities becoming available after the war. Pre-war civil aerodromes, for example [[Sywell Aerodrome|Sywell]], were returned to civilian use.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.sywellaerodrome.co.uk/history.php|title= Sywell Aerodrome <U+2013> History|accessdate=2008-07-05 |publisher= Sywell Aerodrome Ltd.}}</ref> Surplus military airfields were closed, and in some cases, for example [[Beccles Airport|Beccles]], subsequently re-opened as civil aerodromes.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.rainair.co.uk/history.html|title= Fly RainAir (Beccles) <U+2013> History of Beccles (Ellough) Airfield|accessdate=2008-07-05 |publisher= RainAir Flying Club}}</ref> The Ministry of Civil Aviation was created to regulate all civil aviation in the UK, and this task remained the responsibility of government departments until the establishment of the independent CAA in 1972.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.competition-commission.org.uk/rep_pub/reports/1983/fulltext/173c02.pdf |title= Civil Aviation Authority |accessdate=2008-07-14 |publisher= [[Competition Commission|The Monopolies and Mergers Commission]] |date= 1983-11 |pages= ch. 2, p. 4, para. 2.3}}</ref><ref name="CAA_Start"/>

With an expanded infrastructure in place, GA became established after the war when manufacturers such as [[Cessna]] and [[Piper Aircraft|Piper]] introduced [[light aircraft]] designed for the private market. The [[Cessna 172]], developed from the late 1940s [[Cessna 170]], was introduced in 1956, and became the world's best selling single-engine aeroplane.<ref>{{cite journal |url= http://www.airspacemag.com/history-of-flight/cessna.html|title= Cessna's Golden Oldie |accessdate=2008-07-11 |year= 2006 |month=July |journal= Air & Space Magazine}}</ref> Single [[Reciprocating engine|piston]]-engine aircraft are still the most common class of aircraft in the UK GA fleet.<ref name="GA_Aircraft"/> The development of the [[Rogallo wing]] in the 1950s fostered the [[History of hang gliding|development of hang-gliding]] during the 1960s and 1970s.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bmaa.org/histdets.asp?HistoryID=2|title= History of Microlighting <U+2013> 1940<U+2013>1969 |accessdate=2008-07-12 |publisher= British Microlight Aircraft Association}}</ref> The 1960s also saw experiments with motorised [[Hang gliding|hang glider]]s, but it was not until the 1970s that this blend of technologies started to mature, resulting in the birth of the [[Ultralight aviation|microlight]] movement.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bmaa.org/histdets.asp?HistoryID=3|title= History of Microlighting <U+2013> 1970<U+2013>1976 |accessdate=2008-07-12 |publisher= British Microlight Aircraft Association}}</ref> Another milestone in the development of GA was the 1964 introduction of the [[Learjet 23]]. Although it was not the first [[business jet]], it popularised corporate aviation, and established the personal jet as a "whole new class of aircraft".<ref>{{cite journal |url= http://www.airspacemag.com/history-of-flight/Aircraft_That_Changed_the_World.html?c=y&page=4|title= Aircraft That Changed the World |accessdate=2008-07-12 |year= 2008 |month=July |journal= Air & Space Magazine}}</ref>

==Activities==

{{See also|List of general aviation activities}}
{{FixBunching|beg}}
[[Image:Ikarus c42 g-nppl inflight arp.jpg|thumb|right|[[Ikarus C42]] fixed-wing microlight]]
{{FixBunching|mid}}
[[Image:ixess hang glider arp.jpg|thumb|right|[[Air Creation]] Tanarg weight-shift microlight]]
{{FixBunching|mid}}
[[Image:Robinson.r22.g-cbxn.arp.jpg|thumb|right|The development of the [[Robinson R22]] has made recreational helicopter flying more affordable.]]
{{FixBunching|mid}}
[[Image:Hawker_Hunter_-_Elvington_-_BB.jpg|thumb|right|"Miss Demeanour" - privately owned [[Hawker Hunter]]]]
{{FixBunching|end}}
The GA sector operates a range of aircraft, including [[Balloon (aircraft)|balloons]] and [[airship]]s, [[glider]]s, hang gliders, [[Paragliding|paragliders]], microlights, [[Autogyro|gyrocopters]], [[helicopters]], [[Homebuilt aircraft|amateur built]] and mass-produced light aircraft, [[Warbird|ex-military aircraft]], and business jets.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= Overview of the Strategic Review, p. i, para. 1}}</ref> Flights can be broadly categorised as public transport, aerial work, and private flying, the first two of which are commercial activities.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= Overview of the Strategic Review, p. iii, paras. 13 & 16}}</ref>

===Commercial operations===

Commercial operations are remunerated activities which fall within the ICAO definition of CAT. Some are, however, closely aligned to, and considered part of, the GA sector.<ref name="BBGA_Industry"/><ref name="GAAC_Definition"/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= Overview of the Strategic Review, p. iii, paras. 15<U+2013>16}}</ref> Public transport operations are non-scheduled, on-demand services flying between points specified by the customer, providing a more flexible service than [[airline]] travel. [[Air taxi]] operations offer charter services for third parties, and business or corporate aviation uses company-owned aircraft to transport employees and clients. Aircraft used in these operations include business jets, helicopters, and twin piston-engine aeroplanes carrying between six and ten people.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch.1, p. 5, paras. 1.25<U+2013>1.28}}</ref> An example of this type of operation is the transport by helicopter of spectators to the British [[Formula One]] grand prix at [[Silverstone Circuit|Silverstone]]. This involves so many flights that, according to Cranfield Aviation Services, on race day the heliport is temporarily the world<U+2019>s busiest airport.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ghkeurope.com/products/downloads/Publications/EIA_2002%20British_GP.pdf|title= The Economic Impact of the 2002 FIA Foster<U+2019>s British Grand Prix|accessdate=2008-06-14 |publisher= Motorsport Industry Association|date= 2003-07|pages= p. 22, para. 5.7.2}}</ref> Aerial work is a small but important component of the commercial GA sector, characterised in its simplest form as remunerated non-transport activities, such as [[Aerial survey|surveying]], [[Aerial application|crop spraying]], and emergency services work ([[Air Ambulances in the United Kingdom|air ambulance]] and [[Police aviation in the United Kingdom|police]]).<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch.1, p. 4, para. 1.21 & p. 5, para. 1.28}}</ref>

===Flying schools===

Flying schools are commercial businesses engaged in the [[Flight training|training of pilots]], both for recreational purposes and for those intending to fly professionally. They make widespread use of [[Fixed-wing aircraft|fixed-wing]] light aircraft associated with traditional GA, not only for flying lessons but also as club aircraft rented out to qualified pilots for recreational flights. School-owned aircraft account for a significant amount of GA activity, both in terms of hours flown and aircraft movements.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 1, p. 9, para. 1.38}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 1, p. 4, paras. 1.16<U+2013>1.17}}</ref> The pilot training element is regarded by the GA community as a key benefit that is critical to the supply of pilots for the airline industry. It is claimed by the General Aviation Awareness Council that 60<U+2013>70 per cent of professional pilots have self-financed their flight training at GA schools, and one UK airline operator has stated that the industry must rely on 70<U+2013>80 per cent of new pilots coming from the GA sector.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.gaac.co.uk/ga/generalaviationlowres.pdf|title= Why General Aviation?|accessdate=2008-06-17 |publisher= General Aviation Awareness Council|pages= p. 8}} The publication is undated, but is reported in the July 2001 edition of [http://www.ebanmagazine.com/mag_full.html?ident=106 European Business Air News]</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/vo050524/debtext/50524-20.htm|title= House of Commons Hansard for 24 May 2005 (pt 20) |accessdate=2008-06-17 |publisher= [[Hansard]]|date= 2005-05-24|pages= column 618}}</ref> The CAA estimates that between 1996 and 2006 the number of new professional pilots following the unsponsored training route rose from 48 per cent to 59 per cent.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 7, p. 67, para. 7.21}}</ref> The counter argument to this claim is that pilots can be trained outside of the UK, and that the airline industry is not therefore dependent on a healthy GA sector in the UK for its supply of pilots.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 2, p. 17, para. 2.18}}</ref> The CAA concludes that a severe reduction in GA would give "some merit to the argument that pilot recruitment would be threatened", but that the data on flying hours "does not support such a gloomy outlook."<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 2, p. 18, para. 2.24}}</ref>

===Private flying===

Private flying can be for both recreational purposes and personal transport, using aircraft that are owned individually, collectively as part of a syndicate, or rented from a flying club. A survey of pilots conducted between 2001 and 2002 indicated that the most common purposes of recreational flights were local flights near the base aerodrome, visits to other aerodromes, and day trips away.<ref name="GASAR_Activities">{{cite web |url= http://www.gaac.co.uk/gasar/GASAR_NationalPilotSurvey.pdf |title= General Aviation Small Aerodrome Research Study - The National Pilot Survey|accessdate=2008-06-14 |publisher= The Bartlett School, University College London|Author= Terry Lober|date= 2004-08|pages= p. 13}}</ref> Half of all flights landed at the same aerodrome they departed from, and only 9 per cent involved an overnight stay away from home.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.gaac.co.uk/gasar/GASAR_NationalPilotSurvey.pdf |title= General Aviation Small Aerodrome Research Study - The National Pilot Survey|accessdate=2008-06-14 |publisher= The Bartlett School, University College London|Author= Terry Lober|date= 2004-08|pages= p. 11}}</ref>

Private flying is most associated with the traditional form of factory-produced two and four-seater, single piston-engine training and touring aircraft. Examples of these are the [[Cessna 152]], Cessna 172, and [[Piper Cherokee|Piper PA28 Cherokee]], all with their origins in the 1950s, and the more modern designs of [[Cirrus Design|Cirrus]].<ref name="GA_Aircraft">{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 1, p. 3, para. 1.15}}</ref> The average cost per hour to fly such aircraft has been estimated to be <U+00A3>133, compared to an estimated <U+00A3>77 per hour for gliders, and a reported <U+00A3>35 per hour for microlights.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.gaac.co.uk/gasar/GASAR_NationalPilotSurvey.pdf |title= General Aviation Small Aerodrome Research Study - The National Pilot Survey|accessdate=2008-06-14 |publisher= The Bartlett School, University College London|Author= Terry Lober|date= 2004-08|pages= p. 14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.pilotweb.aero/content/articles/view_article.aspx?id=3345 |title= Flying microlights|accessdate=2008-07-18 |publisher= [[Pilot Magazine UK|PilotWeb]] |Author= Dave Calderwood|date= 2005-04-11}}</ref> Recent trends have seen an increase in the use of microlights, and also in recreational helicopter flying following the introduction of smaller and cheaper machines such as the [[Robinson R22]] and [[Robinson R44|R44]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 1, p. 7, para. 1.35 & p. 5, para. 1.29}}</ref> Another growth area in private flying in recent years has been in the use of amateur built aircraft, such as the [[Van's Aircraft RV-4]] and the [[Rutan Long-EZ]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 1, p. 8, para. 1.36}}</ref>

There is a strong vintage aircraft movement in the UK, with two-thirds of the 500 registered historic aircraft active. These cover the whole spectrum of civil and military aviation, examples being the [[de Havilland Dragon Rapide]] airliner of the 1930s, and the [[World War II]] (WWII) [[Supermarine Spitfire|Spitfire]] fighter. There are many post-WWII aircraft which could also be considered historic under a looser definition, including for example 60 ex-military jets such as the [[Hawker Hunter]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 1, p. 5, para. 1.24 and footnote}}</ref> Historic aircraft are regular exhibits at [[Airshow|air displays]], which are claimed to be the second most popular spectator activity after football in the UK.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 1, p. 6, para. 1.30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.gaac.co.uk/ga/generalaviationlowres.pdf|title= Why General Aviation?|accessdate=2008-06-06 |publisher= General Aviation Awareness Council|pages= p. 6}}</ref>

===Sports===

[[Image:Grid AstonDown.jpg|thumb|right|Gliders at the 2004 Standard Class Nationals race]]
[[Gliding competitions|Competetive gliding]] in the UK takes place between May and September. Regionals are local competitions, organised and run by one of the bigger gliding clubs in the region, and represent the entry level to glider racing. Races are handicapped according to glider performance, and normally take place over nine days. Success in the regionals allows pilots to progress to the nationals, where there are five [[Glider Competition Classes|classes]] of competition. These are based on glider performance, the lowest being club class, and then progressing through standard (maximum 15&nbsp;m [[wingspan]], and [[Flap (aircraft)|flaps]] not permitted), 15&nbsp;m (as standard, but flaps are permitted), 18&nbsp;m (maximum 18&nbsp;m wingspan), and finally open-class (no restrictions). Success at national level can lead to a place in the national team and competition at international level.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.lasham.org.uk/comps/introduction/competitions.asp|title= Gliding Competitions|accessdate=2008-07-31 |publisher= Lasham Gliding}}</ref> In 2007 the British gliding team was ranked number one, and British pilots took two women's [[World Gliding Championships|world championships]] and the open class [[European Gliding Championships|European championship]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.glidingteam.co.uk/|title= British Gliding Team website|accessdate=2008-06-06 |publisher= British Gliding Team}}</ref>

[[Handicapping|Handicapped]] [[air racing]] is open to any propeller-driven aircraft capable of maintaining a minimum speed of {{convert|100|mi|km|sigfig=2}} per hour in level flight. Races are a case of "fly low, fly fast, turn left", consisting of 4<U+2013>5 laps round a 20<U+2013>25&nbsp;mile (32<U+2013>40&nbsp;km) circuit. Faster aircraft are handicapped by starting after slower aircraft, the intention being that the race concludes with all aircraft diving for the finish line together.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.airraceuk.co.uk/index.php |title= Handicapped Air Racing|accessdate=2008-06-16 |publisher= [[Royal Aero Club]] Records, Racing and Rally Association}}</ref> There are up to seven races per year, conducted at airfields in the UK, [[France]] and the [[Channel Islands]], for prizes that include the [[Schneider Trophy]] and [[King's Cup Race|King's Cup]], and the season culminates with the British Air Racing and European Air Racing Championships.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.airraceuk.co.uk/modules.php?name=News&file=article&sid=9&mode=&order=0&thold=0 |title= Lets Go Racing! - 2008 Season Dates|accessdate=2008-06-16 |publisher= [[Royal Aero Club]] Records, Racing and Rally Association}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.airraceuk.co.uk/modules.php?name=About_Us|title= About us|accessdate=2008-06-16 |publisher= [[Royal Aero Club]] Records, Racing and Rally Association}}</ref>

[[Image:Extra.ea300s.g-iiui.arp.jpg|thumb|left|[[Extra 300]] Unlimited class aerobatic aircraft]]
[[Competition aerobatics|Aerobatic competitions]] take place for both powered aircraft and gliders, with up to 30 events each year in the UK and [[<U+00C9>ire]].<ref name="BAeA_Home">{{cite web |url= http://www.aerobatics.org.uk/ |title= British Aerobatic Association website home page|accessdate=2008-06-16 |publisher= [[British Aerobatic Association]]}}</ref> Starting at the Beginner level, pilots can move up to Standard (powered aircraft) or Sports (glider) levels, and then on to Intermediate, Advanced, and finally Unlimited classes. Each step up requires a wider repertoire of [[Aerobatics|aerobatic]] figures and progressively more performance from the aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.aerobatics.org.uk/CIB2008_BAeAweb_v2.pdf |title= Contest Information Booklet for 2008|accessdate=2008-06-16 |publisher= [[British Aerobatic Association]] |pages= pp. 5<U+2013>6 |date= 2008}}</ref> National championships are awarded annually at Standard/Sports, Intermediate, Advanced (powered aircraft only), and Unlimited levels,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.aerobatics.org.uk/results/2006/champions_2006.htm |title= BAeA Champions and Trophy holders in 2006|accessdate=2008-06-16 |publisher= [[British Aerobatic Association]]}}</ref> and pilots who have reached Advanced and Unlimited levels are eligible for selection to represent the UK in international competition.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.aerobatics.org.uk/CIB2008_BAeAweb_v2.pdf |title= Contest Information Booklet for 2008|accessdate=2008-06-16 |publisher= [[British Aerobatic Association]] |pages= p. 6 |date= 2008}}</ref>

[[Parachuting|Parachute]] competitions are held at club, regional, national and international levels, and include the disciplines of [[accuracy landing]]s, [[Freefall style|freefall gymnastics]], [[formation skydiving]], [[canopy formation]], [[Freestyle skydiving|freestyle]] and [[freeflying]], and [[skysurfing]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bpa.org.uk/comp.htm |title= Competition Dives |accessdate=2008-07-14 |publisher= [[British Parachute Association]]}}</ref> British teams consistently win medals in canopy formation world championships, and a British team took the 2006 world championship in women's 4-way formation skydiving.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bpa.org.uk/comp4.htm |title= Canopy Formation |accessdate=2008-07-14 |publisher= [[British Parachute Association]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bpa.org.uk/comp3.htm |title= Team Formation Skydiving |accessdate=2008-07-14 |publisher= [[British Parachute Association]]}}</ref>
{{-}}

==Aerodromes==

[[Image:East Midlands2.JPG|thumb|right|[[East Midlands Airport]] - classified by GASAR as a regional airport]]
{{See also|List of airports in the United Kingdom}}
''Aerodrome'' is a collective term for any location from which flying operations take place, although more specific terminology can be used to characterise its purpose. The CAA strategic review of GA applies the term ''[[airport]]'' to locations which predominantly support large scale commercial operations, and ''airfield'' to locations which predominantly support GA operations.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 3, pp. 29<U+2013>30, paras. 3.36 & 3.45}}</ref> The ''General Aviation Small Aerodrome Research Study'' (GASAR) analysed 687 aerodromes in [[England]] which come under the scope of GA, classifying 374 into six types. These range in size from regional airports to the smallest farm strip, although 84 per cent of GA flights operate from 134 of the larger aerodromes in the first four categories.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.gaac.co.uk/gasar/GASAR_AerodromeCategorisation.pdf |title= General Aviation Small Aerodrome Research Study - Aerodrome Categorisation Using Secondary Aerodrome Data|accessdate=2008-06-06 |publisher= The Bartlett School, University College London|Author= Terry Lober|date= 2004-09|pages= pp. 2<U+2013>3}} Of the 687 aerodromes, 113 were used for glider, microlight, balloon and parascending operations which were nowhere described in detail, and could not therefore be included in the classification analysis, and 200 sites were identified as [[helipad]]s; a distinct category without further need for classification analysis according to the requirements of the study, leaving 374 which were included in the classification analysis.</ref><ref name="GASAR_Aerodrome_Qty"/>

===GASAR aerodrome classification===

The factors used in determining how an individual aerodrome is categorised by the GASAR study are based broadly on size and facilities. The six types of aerodrome are described, in size order, as: regional airports (e.g. [[East Midlands Airport|East Midlands]]); major GA airports (e.g. [[Oxford Airport|Oxford]]); developed GA airfields (e.g. [[Andrewsfield Airport|Andrewsfield]]); basic GA airfields (e.g. [[Rufforth]]); developed airstrips (e.g. [[Tilstock Airfield|Tilstock]]); and basic airstrips.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.gaac.co.uk/gasar/GASAR_AerodromeCategorisation.pdf |title= General Aviation Small Aerodrome Research Study - Aerodrome Categorisation Using Secondary Aerodrome Data|accessdate=2008-06-06 |publisher= The Bartlett School, University College London|Author= Terry Lober|date= 2004-09|pages= pp. 2<U+2013>5}} The actual criteria used to categorise aerodromes were complex, using 28 different parameters, backed up with a peer review by experienced GA pilots.</ref>

[[Image:Andrewsfield Airport from the air in 1991.jpg|thumb|left|[[Andrewsfield Airport|Andrewsfield]] - classified by GASAR as a developed GA airfield]]
Airports generally have long, fully lit, hard-surfaced runways, full [[air traffic control]], and [[Radio navigation|navigation]] and [[Instrument approach|landing]] aids. They are usually located on urban fringes, support commercial and business operations, and often exclude certain types of light aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.gaac.co.uk/gasar/GASAR_AerodromeCategorisation.pdf |title= General Aviation Small Aerodrome Research Study - Aerodrome Categorisation Using Secondary Aerodrome Data|accessdate=2008-06-06 |publisher= The Bartlett School, University College London|Author= Terry Lober|date= 2004-09|pages= pp. 5<U+2013>6}}</ref> At the more rurally located airfields, the lighter end of aviation, such as microlight and gliding activities, becomes increasingly prevalent, and there are few or no commercial operations other than flying schools. At this level runways are generally shorter, and grass surfaces are increasingly common. Navigation aids are increasingly scarce, being more basic where they are available, and informal ground to air radio communication replaces air traffic control. The smallest airfields are too small to feature on general purpose [[Ordnance Survey]] (OS) maps, and lack basic facilities such as fuel and maintenance.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.gaac.co.uk/gasar/GASAR_AerodromeCategorisation.pdf |title= General Aviation Small Aerodrome Research Study - Aerodrome Categorisation Using Secondary Aerodrome Data|accessdate=2008-06-06 |publisher= The Bartlett School, University College London|Author= Terry Lober|date= 2004-09|pages= pp. 6<U+2013>8}}</ref> The majority of airstrips are basically single short grass runways with no supporting facilities, although the presence of a hangar is not uncommon at the larger examples. They do not feature on OS maps, and are owned by private clubs or, more commonly, individuals.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.gaac.co.uk/gasar/GASAR_AerodromeCategorisation.pdf |title= General Aviation Small Aerodrome Research Study - Aerodrome Categorisation Using Secondary Aerodrome Data|accessdate=2008-06-06 |publisher= The Bartlett School, University College London|Author= Terry Lober|date= 2004-09|pages= pp. 8<U+2013>10}}</ref>

===Aerodrome licensing===

Most aerodromes used for public transport operations, and all those used for powered flight training operations, are required to be licensed by the CAA.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/33/CAP168.PDF|title= CAP 168 Licensing of Aerodromes|accessdate=2008-06-12 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2007-02-27|pages= p. 1, para. 2}}</ref> To be granted a licence an aerodrome operator must satisfy the CAA that: the physical conditions at the aerodrome, and its environs, are acceptable; the scale of equipment, and facilities provided, are adequate for the flying activities which are expected to take place; an effective safety management system is in place; and that staff are competent and, where necessary, suitably qualified.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/33/CAP168.PDF|title= CAP 168 Licensing of Aerodromes|accessdate=2008-06-12 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2007-02-27|pages= ch. 1, p. 6, para. 5.1}}</ref> Aerodromes classified as developed GA airfields or larger by the GASAR study are, with few exceptions, licensed. Only two basic GA airfields, [[Silverstone Heliport|Silverstone]] and [[Duxford Aerodrome|Duxford]], are licensed, and all airstrips are unlicensed.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.gaac.co.uk/gasar/GASAR_AerodromeCategorisation.pdf |title= General Aviation Small Aerodrome Research Study - Aerodrome Categorisation Using Secondary Aerodrome Data|accessdate=2008-06-06 |publisher= The Bartlett School, University College London|Author= Terry Lober|date= 2004-09|pages= pp. 5<U+2013>10}}</ref> The Light Aviation Airports Study Group, a joint CAA-industry initiative, was established in 2005 to review the regulation of light aviation aerodromes. A particular focus of this group was a review of the restrictions placed on unlicensed aerodromes.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/17/srg_asd_laasgfinalreport_16-01-06.pdf|title= Final report to the CAA Executive Committee |accessdate=2008-07-23 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-01-16|pages= p. 1, para. 1.1}}</ref> The group concluded that the requirement for public transport operations to be conducted only from licensed aerodromes should be further reviewed in the context of corresponding international and European requirements. It also recommended that restrictions on flight training at unlicensed aerodromes should be lifted, and a consultation to this effect was started in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/17/srg_asd_laasgfinalreport_16-01-06.pdf|title= Final report to the CAA Executive Committee |accessdate=2008-07-23 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-01-16|pages= p. 4, para. 5.6 & p. 5, para 9.1}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1710/CL%2001-08%20-%20LAASG%20FTSG%20ANO%20Amendment%20Proposal%20-%20v%20%201.00.00%20-%2007%20Apr%2008.pdf|title= Consultation on The Light Aviation Airports Study Group (LAASG) FTSG Proposals |accessdate=2008-07-23 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2008-04-07}}</ref>

==Scale of the sector==

[[Image:Hangglider103042006.jpg|thumb|right|There are 7,000 hang gliders registered in the UK]]
There are an estimated 27,000 civil aircraft registered in the UK, 96&nbsp;per&nbsp;cent of which are engaged in GA activities. In 2005 the GA fleet comprised 9,000 fixed-wing aircraft, 4,100 microlights, 1,300 helicopters, 1,800 airships/balloons, 2,500 gliders and some 7,000 hang gliders. Estimates put the number of foreign-registered GA aircraft based in the UK at 900.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= Overview of the Strategic Review, pp. iii<U+2013>iv, paras. 17, 19 & 20}}</ref>

The number of pilots licensed by the CAA to fly powered aircraft in 2005 was 47,000, of whom 28,000 held a [[Private Pilot Licence]]. The remainder held professional pilot licences, either a [[Commercial Pilot Licence]] or an [[Airline Transport Pilot Licence]], although not all of these would be engaged in GA activities.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= Overview of the Strategic Review, p. v, para. 24}}</ref> In addition, there are 10,000 active glider pilots,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.gliding.co.uk/press/releases/2003/Gliding%20in%20UK.doc|title= Press Information|accessdate=2008-06-16 |publisher= [[British Gliding Association]]}}</ref> and estimates put the membership of aviation-related sport and recreational associations at 36,000.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 2, p. 22, para. 2.37}}</ref> 

The number of aerodromes that support GA in the UK is difficult to establish with certainty. ''Pooleys 2008 United Kingdom Flight Guide'' lists 355,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.pooleys.com/prod_detail.cfm?product_id=641 |title= Pooleys 2008 United Kingdom Flight Guide |accessdate=2008-06-09 |publisher= Pooleys Flight Equipment Ltd.|date= 2008-01-01}}</ref> and the Airplan Flight Equipment ''UK VFR Flight Guide 2008'' lists nearly 500.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.afeonline.com/shop/product_info.php?products_id=160 |title= UK VFR Flight Guide 2008 |accessdate=2008-06-09 |publisher= Airplan Flight Equipment Ltd.|date= 2008}}</ref> Lockyears ''Farm 'Strips' and Private Airfields Flight Guide'' lists more than 300 landing sites.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.pooleys.com/prod_detail.cfm?product_id=120 |title= Farm 'Strips' and Private Airfields Flight Guide |accessdate=2008-06-09 |publisher= Seaton Sands Limited (Aviation Division)|date= 2008}}</ref> The GASAR study estimates 1,100 formal flying sites in England alone, a figure which includes 400 sites known to planning authorities but not included in flight guides. It estimates another 759 informal sites known only to land owners, customs, and members of the enthusiast group Air-Britain.<ref name="GASAR_Aerodrome_Qty">{{cite web |url= http://www.gaac.co.uk/gasar/GASAR_Conclusions.pdf |title= General Aviation Small Aerodrome Research Study - A review, for the GASR team, of the GASAR papers and conclusions reached|accessdate=2008-06-14 |publisher= The Bartlett School, University College London|Author= Terry Lober|date= 2006-03|pages= p. 6}}</ref>

The sector was estimated to employ nearly 12,000 people and directly contribute <U+00A3>1.4&nbsp;billion to the UK economy in 2005, making it roughly seven&nbsp;per&nbsp;cent of the size of the CAT industry. Nearly half of the economic contribution was generated by business aviation.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.gaac.co.uk/gasar/GASAR_GAsocio-economic_Rev1.pdf |title= General Aviation Small Aerodrome Research Study - An estimate of the annual direct socio-economic contribution of GA to the UK economy|accessdate=2008-06-03 |publisher= The Bartlett School, University College London|Author= Terry Lober|date= 2006-03-25|pages= pp. 18<U+2013>19}}</ref>

==Trends==

[[Image:Piper.seneca.pa34.g-elis.bristol.arp.jpg|thumb|left|The number of registered twin piston-engined aircraft is on the decline.]]
Most sectors of GA for which data are available have experienced growth in aircraft numbers and hours flown over the last two decades. The lighter end of the GA spectrum: microlights, amateur built, and airships and balloons, have in particular shown strong growth, although the last of these activities was severely curtailed during the [[2001 United Kingdom foot-and-mouth crisis|foot-and-mouth outbreak]] in 2001, when access to farmland was denied .<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 1, pp. 7<U+2013>8, paras. 1.34<U+2013>1.36}}</ref> After strong growth in the late 1980s, traditional flying has shown a slight decline recently, reflecting a move amongst recreational flyers towards microlight aircraft, and increased numbers of foreign-registered aircraft. Recreational helicopter usage has grown primarily due to the introduction of smaller and cheaper aircraft. Glider activity has remained relatively static, although there has been a gradual increase in the number of [[Motor glider|self-launching motor gliders]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 1, pp. 9 & 13<U+2013>14, paras. 1.37 & 1.46<U+2013>1.48}}</ref>

Business aviation has shown strong growth, although the numbers of aircraft on the UK register have declined. This reflects a shift away from [[turboprop]] aircraft towards foreign-registered business jets based in the UK, which are estimated to be growing in numbers. However, twin piston-engined aircraft numbers have declined significantly, reflecting pressures on the light air-taxi segment from increasingly flexible and cheaper scheduled services, and a more sophisticated corporate charter business.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 1, pp. 10<U+2013>12, paras. 1.40<U+2013>1.45}}</ref> The amount of flight training conducted by UK schools has declined, largely at the hands of competition from foreign schools, which benefit from lower costs and better weather.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 1, pp. 9<U+2013>10, paras. 1.38<U+2013>1.39}}</ref>

Since 1990 the total number of hours flown annually by the GA sector has remained in the range 1.25<U+2013>1.35&nbsp;million, the dominant sector being traditional GA flying, which accounts for 0.6&nbsp;million per year. An overall increase in aircraft numbers combined with nil growth in hours flown has brought the annual average utilisation per aircraft down from 157 hours in 1984 to 103 hours in 2002. The decline in asset utilisation has lead to speculation that the economic health of the GA industry is weakening, though the lack of data on profitability makes this difficult to confirm.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= Overview of the Strategic Review, pp. vi<U+2013>vii, paras. 30<U+2013>31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.gaac.co.uk/gasar/GASAR_AnalysisHoursFlown.pdf |title= General Aviation Small Aerodrome Research Study - An analysis of CAA data regarding the number of GA aircraft and hours flown for the years 1984 to 2001 |accessdate=2008-07-25 |publisher= The Bartlett School, University College London|Author= Terry Lober|date= 2005-12|pages= p. 3}}</ref>

==Regulation==

{{FixBunching|beg}}
[[Image:Genav.vansrv4.arp.750pix.jpg|thumb|right|[[Van's Aircraft RV-4]] amateur built aircraft]]
{{FixBunching|mid}}
[[Image:SpitfireDuxford2JM.jpg|thumb|right|A British [[warbird]] - the Grace [[Supermarine Spitfire|Spitfire]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ml407.co.uk/pages/main.html|title= Grace Spitfire ML 407|accessdate=2008-06-15 |publisher= Grace Spitfire Official Website}}</ref>]]
{{FixBunching|mid}}
[[Image:Dragon rapide g-aeml flying arp.jpg|thumb|right|[[de Havilland Dragon Rapide]] vintage aircraft]]
{{FixBunching|mid}}
[[Image:Bristol International Balloon Fiesta.JPG|thumb|right|Mass balloon ascent at the [[Bristol International Balloon Fiesta]]]]
{{FixBunching|end}}
The objective of regulation is to "promote high standards of safety in all aspects of aviation", and this is the main area of interaction between the CAA and the GA sector.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 4, p. 36, para. 4.7}}</ref> Efforts focus on assuring appropriate standards of [[airworthiness]], [[Pilot licensing in the United Kingdom|pilot qualification]], the rules for the movement of aircraft, and equipment to be carried.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/33/RegReview.pdf|title= Regulatory Review of General Aviation in the United Kingdom|accessdate=2008-06-03 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07-06|pages= p. 4<U+2013>2}}</ref> The CAA was established as the primary regulatory body for all aviation in the UK in 1972.<ref name="CAA_Start">{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/33/RegReview.pdf|title= Regulatory Review of General Aviation in the United Kingdom|accessdate=2008-06-03 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07-06|pages= pp. 4<U+2013>1 to 4<U+2013>2, para. 4.2}}</ref> In 1991 it started working within the [[Joint Aviation Authorities]] (JAA) framework to implement agreed common standards, known as the Joint Aviation Requirements (JAR), throughout the [[European Union]] (EU). In 2003 this was taken a step further when the [[European Aviation Safety Agency]] (EASA) was established as the central EU regulator, taking over responsibility for legislating airworthiness and environmental regulation from the national authorities. The CAA acts as an agency of EASA on these issues, retaining its original regulatory powers in areas not yet transferred to EASA. Proposed developments seek to establish EASA as the single authority throughout the EU, taking over from individual member states the power to regulate all aviation other than that specifically excluded from the scope of EASA.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 5, pp. 52<U+2013>53, paras. 5.18<U+2013>5.24}}</ref> 

===Devolved and self-regulation===

Within this framework certain sectors of GA are governed on a devolved basis. In all cases the CAA/EASA retains responsibility for safety regulation, but representative bodies, particularly of sectors that are not included in the scope of EASA, are granted greater oversight of their activities.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 1, p. 1, para. 1.4}}</ref> The majority of microlight aircraft are regulated by the British Microlight Aircraft Association, although a significant number are regulated by the Light Aircraft Association (LAA), formerly known as the [[Popular Flying Association]]. The LAA is the primary regulator for amateur built aircraft, as well as vintage and classic aircraft. Parachuting is governed by the [[British Parachute Association]], although the aircraft used in this activity are generally CAA-regulated. Balloon and airship flying is overseen by the British Balloon and Airship Club.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 1, pp. 2<U+2013>3, paras. 1.6<U+2013>1.10}}</ref> The UK-specific National Private Pilot Licence (NPPL) is administered by the National Pilots Licensing Group Ltd., supported by the LAA, the [[Aircraft Owners and Pilots Association]] UK, the [[British Gliding Association]], and the British Microlight Aircraft Association.<ref name="LASORS_NPPL">{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/175/Section%20C%20-%20PRIVATE%20PILOT%20LICENCE.pdf|title= Licensing, Administration and Standardisation; Operating Requirements and Safety (LASORS) - Section C Private Pilot Licence|accessdate=2008-06-12 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2008|pages= p. 20}}</ref> Separate from these devolved groups, gliding in the UK is self-regulated. The British Gliding Association was until recently responsible for glider airworthiness, now formally regulated as a result of EASA legislation, and still retains control of pilot certification. Hang gliding and paragliding activities (i.e. foot-launched gliders) are governed by the British Hang Gliding and Paragliding Association.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 1, p. 3, paras. 1.11<U+2013>1.13}}</ref>

===Airworthiness===

Under CAA and EASA rules, all aircraft are required to meet certain standards of airworthiness to fly safely and legally. Aircraft that meet these standards are issued with a Certificate of Airworthiness. However, British-registered aircraft which are excluded from the scope of EASA, and which cannot satisfy the requirements for the issue of a Certificate of Airworthiness, may be issued with a Permit to Fly. This allows them to fly in UK airspace subject to certain limitations, for example being restricted to day-time flights under [[visual flight rules]] only. Permits are typically issued to vintage and historic aircraft, amateur built aircraft, and microlights.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/33/CAP733.PDF|title= CAP 733 Permit to Fly Aircraft|accessdate=2008-06-11 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2004-06-28|pages= ch. 1, pp. 1<U+2013>2}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 1, pp. 2<U+2013>3, paras. 1.7<U+2013>1.9}}</ref>

===Pilot licensing===

{{main|Pilot licensing in the United Kingdom}}
The pilot qualification most relevant to GA is the Private Pilot Licence (PPL), which permits the holder to fly for recreational purposes without remuneration.<ref name="LASORS_Remun">{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/175/Section%20A%20-%20GENERAL%20INFORMATION%20(LASORS).pdf|title= Licensing, Administration and Standardisation; Operating Requirements and Safety (LASORS) - Section A General Information|accessdate=2008-06-12 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2008|pages= p. 4}}</ref> In addition to the European-wide Joint Aviation Regulations Flight Crew Licensing (JAR-FCL) standard, the CAA also issues UK-specific national licences. In the absence of European standards for gyroplane, balloon, and airship pilots, the CAA licenses these according to the original UK PPL standard.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/175/Section%20C%20-%20PRIVATE%20PILOT%20LICENCE.pdf|title= Licensing, Administration and Standardisation; Operating Requirements and Safety (LASORS) - Section C Private Pilot Licence|accessdate=2008-06-12 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2008|pages= p. 1}}</ref> As a response to the perception that JAR pilot licensing standards are excessively bureaucratic and expensive for the purposes of recreational pilots, the National Private Pilot Licence (NPPL) was introduced in 2002.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.aopa.co.uk/scripts/nppl.php|title= The National Private Pilot's Licence (NPPL)|accessdate=2008-06-13 |publisher= [[Aircraft Owners and Pilots Association]] UK}}</ref> The NPPL is easier to obtain than the JAR-FCL licence, has less stringent medical requirements, is more restrictive in the privileges it grants, and is valid only for flights in British-registered aircraft flying in UK airspace.<ref name="LASORS_NPPL"/> Although there are plans to bring glider pilot licensing within the regulatory framework of EASA,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.gliding.co.uk/bgainfo/nppl/futurelicensing.htm|title= Future Licensing|accessdate=2008-06-13 |publisher= [[British Gliding Association]]}}</ref> the gliding sector is currently self-regulating in this respect. The British Gliding Association is responsible for defining the standards of initial training, and certifying, via a badge system, pilots who meet those standards.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.gliding.co.uk/bgainfo/nppl/introduction.htm|title= Pilot Licensing Introduction|accessdate=2008-06-13 |publisher= [[British Gliding Association]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.gliding.co.uk/learningtoglide/thebadgesystem.htm|title= The Badge System|accessdate=2008-06-13 |publisher= [[British Gliding Association]]}}</ref> Pilots working in sectors of GA that are commercial operations, such as aerial work and business aviation, are required to hold a professional pilot licence which, at a minimum, is the Commercial Pilot Licence.<ref name="LASORS_Remun"/>

==Safety==

[[Image:Broken propeller.jpg|thumb|upright|left]]
Between 1995 and 2004 there were 2,630 accidents involving GA aircraft, of which 139 were fatal, resulting in the loss of 317 lives. The majority of accidents involved small fixed-wing aircraft engaged in private flights, and analysis attributes the most common causes of these to: flight handling skills; poor judgement or [[airmanship]]; lack of training or experience; and omission of, or inappropriate, action.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/33/CAP763.pdf|title= CAP 763 Aviation Safety Review 2005|accessdate=2008-06-21 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-08-08|pages= ch. 5, pp. 5<U+2013>6, para. 3.6}}</ref>

