There were 27 fatal accidents involving GA aircraft in 2007, resulting in the loss of 48 lives. These compare with 16 accidents claiming a total of 19 lives the previous year, and although the 2007 statistics are higher than average, they are not exceptional.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/978/GeneralAviation.pdf|title= SRG Safety Plan 2008 Update|accessdate=2008-06-22 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2008-06|pages= p. 49}}</ref>

==Issues==

The growth in Commercial Air Transport (CAT) has eroded the operational freedom of GA, both in the air and on the ground at larger airports. Difficulties with access to larger airports is compounded by a decline in the number of aerodromes generally, and existing sites are often threatened with closure and re-development for more profitable uses. The UK [[Town and country planning in the United Kingdom|planning system]] is designed to focus on local issues, and consideration of the national impact of GA operations is not within its remit. This makes aerodrome development difficult, often subjecting those that successfully negotiate the process to restrictions in use.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 3}}</ref>

===Access to airspace===

[[Image:Birmingham Airport, England, Feb. 2008.jpg|thumb|right|In [[Airspace_class#United_Kingdom|controlled airspace]] above [[Birmingham International Airport (United Kingdom)|Birmingham Airport]]]]
[[Airspace]] is shared by CAT, [[Military aviation|military]] and GA users. It is divided into [[controlled airspace]], in which aircraft must always be under the control of an [[air traffic controller]], and [[uncontrolled airspace]], in which aircraft can operate autonomously.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 3, p. 23, para. 3.7}}</ref> Although GA flights can under certain conditions enter controlled airspace, they operate mainly outside of it.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 3, p. 24, para. 3.9}}</ref> Controlled airspace is essential for the provision of a known air traffic environment necessary for the safe operation of CAT, and mixing operations with other users is "considered undesirable, even untenable".<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 3, p. 26, para. 3.22}}</ref> Increases in the number of CAT operations, and in the number of airports they operate from, has resulted in a corresponding increase in controlled airspace. Between 1997 and 2006 this area grew in size from 13 per cent of all airspace to 22 per cent nationally, and from 24 per cent to 43 per cent in airspace above England and [[Wales]], leading to a perception within the GA community of being squeezed out. There are particular problems for GA around large airports, where controlled airspace extends to ground level. The concentration of commercial operations and high demand for GA in the South East of England have also resulted in extensive areas of controlled airspace there, which serve to channel uncontrolled GA operations through high-collision-risk hot spots.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 3, pp. 24<U+2013>25, paras. 3.13<U+2013>3.16}}</ref>

===Aerodrome access===

[[Image:Gatwick, 1960.jpg|thumb|right|Light aircraft parked at [[London Gatwick Airport]] in 1961, before it became a CAT giant]]
Regional airports, such as [[Southampton Airport]], have experienced strong growth in CAT operations in recent years. These operations are commercially and operationally incompatible with GA, and although there is no evidence of unfair discrimination, the effect has been to discourage or exclude it. GA aircraft are being subject to significant increases in charges, including the imposition of handling fees in some cases. Some airports restrict or deny GA parking, and others limit or refuse certain GA activity.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 3, pp. 29<U+2013>30, paras. 3.13<U+2013>3.16}}</ref>

In addition to this de facto loss of facilities, the number of aerodromes in the UK has been in decline over the last 50 years, as a result of increasing urbanisation and the rationalisation of WWII airfields. Alternative and more profitable uses for land can also lead to existing aerodromes being threatened with closure, for example [[North Weald Airfield|North Weald]], or actually being closed, as happened to [[Ipswich Airport]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.northwealdairfield.org/Campaign/campaign.html|title= Campaign to Save North Weald Airfield|accessdate=2008-06-18 |publisher= North Weald Airfield Users Group}} North Weald is waiting on a decision concerning closure and re-development for residential purposes.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ipswichairport.info/history.html|title= Ipswich Airport History|accessdate=2008-06-18 |publisher= Ipswich Airport Association}} Ipswich Airport was closed in 1996 and the land turned over to residential re-development.</ref> Referring to the importance of a "functioning national network of GA airfields", especially where GA performs an air transport role, the CAA states that "there could be cause for concern if a significant further loss of airfields were to continue, especially if crucial nodes on the transport network were to be lost."<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 3, p. 33, para. 3.59 and p. 28, paras. 3.33 & 3.35}} 'Crucial nodes' are aerodromes for which "...there are no nearby alternatives...", and the loss of which "...may have a greater effect nationally, or in terms of regional economic development, than would be considered if only assessing the local effect."</ref>

===Planning system===

The planning system is critical to the viability and operation of GA aerodromes.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 3, p. 32, para. 3.49}}</ref> With many cities lacking scheduled air transport services between them, and with GA access to commercial airports becoming increasingly difficult and expensive, a viable network of aerodromes supporting GA air transport operations is regarded as an important national issue.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 2, pp. 18<U+2013>19, paras. 2.25<U+2013>2.27}}</ref> However, there is no unified national planning policy specific to GA aerodromes, and planning decisions relating to these are based on local issues that are not required to consider the national impact.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 3, pp. 33<U+2013>34, paras. 3.58<U+2013>3.61}}</ref> Because aircraft are excluded from noise control legislation, the only recourse for people affected by aircraft noise is through the planning process, and this issue is the principal factor on which the majority of planning decisions relating to GA land use are made.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/7/20080229NoiseConsiderationsAtGAAerodromes-CAAGuidance.pdf|title= Noise Considerations at General Aviation (GA) Aerodromes|accessdate=2008-06-21 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2008-02-27|pages= ch. 3, pp. 1<U+2013>2, para. 3.2}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.gaac.co.uk/factsheets/GAAC-PPG24-report.pdf|title= A review of the application of Planning Policy Guidance Note PPG 24 to General Aviation airfields, with proposals for improved guidance|accessdate=2008-06-21 |publisher= General Aviation Awareness Council|date= 2002-12|pages= ch. 1, p. 2, para. 1.1}}</ref> GA is a specialist subject often unfamiliar to [[Local planning authority|Local Planning Authorities]], and most planning decisions relating to GA either refuse permission, or grant it with restrictive conditions.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= Appendix 6, p. 146, paras. 28<U+2013>29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.gaac.co.uk/factsheets/GAAC-PPG24-report.pdf|title= A review of the application of Planning Policy Guidance Note PPG 24 to General Aviation airfields, with proposals for improved guidance|accessdate=2008-06-21 |publisher= General Aviation Awareness Council|date= 2002-12|pages= ch. 1, p. 2, paras. 1.2<U+2013>1.4}}</ref> [[Little Gransden Airfield|Little Gransden]] is just one example of a GA airfield required to comply with planning restrictions on the number of movements permitted, thereby inhibiting further development.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 2, p. 19}}</ref> Such restrictions, if poorly conceived, can make GA operations unviable or even unsafe.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 3, p. 33, paras. 3.56<U+2013>3.57}}</ref>

==Criticism==

[[Image:569897100 4e449041ab.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Parachute dropping is just one of the GA activities that generate noise complaints]]
Public opinion towards aviation generally is worsening, based on increasing [[Aviation and the environment|environmental concerns]] relating to emissions and [[Aircraft noise|noise]], and private flying has been criticised by respondents to a government consultation on aircraft noise as a frivolous or selfish activity.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority (United Kingdom)|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= Overview of the Strategic Review, p. iii, para. 15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dft.gov.uk/pgr/aviation/environmentalissues/controlofnoisefromcivilaircr2877|title= Control of Noise from Civil Aircraft The Government<U+2019>s conclusions|accessdate=2008-06-23 |publisher= [[Department for Transport]]|date= 2003-12|pages= p. 6}}</ref> In terms of environmental complaints and enquiries made to the CAA that relate specifically to GA, noise is "by far" the most common subject.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/7/20080229NoiseConsiderationsAtGAAerodromes-CAAGuidance.pdf|title= Noise Considerations at General Aviation (GA) Aerodromes|accessdate=2008-06-23 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= p. 1, para. 1.1}}</ref> Half of the 2,000 noise complaints made annually to the CAA concern GA operations, most of which relate to aerobatics, helicopters using private sites, air balloon incidents, parachute dropping, and alleged low flying.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/1/strateg%20review.pdf|title= Strategic Review of General Aviation in the UK|accessdate=2008-06-04 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority of the United Kingdom|CAA]]|date= 2006-07|pages= ch. 2, p. 21, paras. 2.31<U+2013>2.34}}</ref>

Planning guidance on aircraft noise advises that "in some circumstances the public perceive general aircraft noise levels as more disturbing than similar levels around major airports."<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.communities.gov.uk/documents/planningandbuilding/pdf/156558.pdf|title= Planning Policy Guidance 24: Planning and Noise|accessdate=2008-07-14 |publisher= Department for Communities and Local Government|date= 1994-09|pages= Annex 3, para. 7}}</ref> This is a result of the tonal characteristics of light aircraft engines and the activities they are engaged in, including: repetitive [[Airfield traffic pattern|circuit flying]] at low-altitude near an aerodrome, during which aircraft are audible for long periods; slow climbing aircraft engaged in parachute drop or glider tug activities concentrated around the [[drop zone]] or aerodrome, also audible for long periods; erratic and repetitive engine noise from aircraft engaged in aerobatics; and piston-engines on full power in areas of low background noise, leading to the perception that such noise is more intrusive.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/7/20080229NoiseConsiderationsAtGAAerodromes-CAAGuidance.pdf |title= Noise Considerations at General Aviation (GA) Aerodromes|accessdate=2008-06-14 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority (United Kingdom)|CAA]]|date= 2008-02-27|pages= p. 3, para. 5.1}}</ref> In an attempt to alleviate these problems, the majority of aerodromes implement noise abatement procedures designed to route aircraft away from noise sensitive areas, and more than 50 are required by the government to provide consultative facilities in which local concerns can be raised with aerodrome operators.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.caa.co.uk/docs/7/20080229NoiseConsiderationsAtGAAerodromes-CAAGuidance.pdf |title= Noise Considerations at General Aviation (GA) Aerodromes|accessdate=2008-06-14 |publisher= [[Civil Aviation Authority (United Kingdom)|CAA]]|date= 2008-02-27|pages= p. 3, section 6 and p. 8, para. 9.5}}</ref>
{{-}}

